<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Original Windows Vista Taskbar]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=6604&amp;p=28876#p28876"><![CDATA[
I too, like the darker is better. <img src="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/images/smilies/icon_e_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br />That's the way I always remember Vista, from fresh install.<br /><br />Quite nice too on totally transparent setting. <br /><br />For myself on glass, I take it a little further, <br />by adding the alpha channel, to grab some more of the glass color. <br />200/255 is always a good starting point for alpha values.<br /><br />It's an odd relationship with glass color and opacity.<br />I'll try to explain, from the way I notice.<br /><br />The opacity CSM settings behave differently than in the image bitmaps, of taskbars, and menus.<br />With CSM settings with opacity at 0 percent, both the glass color and opacity is reduced.<br />Where as,<br />if the bitmaps have 0 percent instead, the opacity is reduced, <br />but the glass color increases even if there is no glass mask set.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=856">juniper7</a> — Thu Aug 25, 2016 1:29 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
